segments.text: What made our class, I think, individually different is that we all came from modest families.
We all had a work ethic we had to have to be there and get through.
And it brought us closer together.
Back to these student organizations.
Was there an Aggie band in those days?
Oh, yes, we had an Aggie band.
Please describe it and what it meant to the campus.
Well, the Aggie band has always been special.
One of my closest friends, General O.R.
Simpson, was in the Aggie band and came here in the Aggie band.
He was in my graduating class in high school.
I'd lay out two years and he'd go to sea, but he went directly to A&M.
And he was a great influence on my life and one of my dearest friends today, although I see him seldom because his wife is still quite ill and he's become more or less of a cruise, you know.
I saw him not long ago at lunch.
He and I became friends when he came back to A&M.
I remember when he came, first time I met him, he was the reviewing officer and the commissioning speaker.
And I remember that very erect carriage in that pure white uniform.
Well, I can tell you a story about him.
It'll be of interest.
When he graduated in 1936,
I followed him and graduated in 37, about a year really apart.
When he graduated, there was only one appointment in the armed services as a regular commissioner.
That was the Marine Corps.
And he was the number one military graduate, and it was given to him.
And he went to the Marine Corps at Quanto, Virginia,
And I remember when he was very much in love with Roger Miller of Bryan, Texas.
So much so that he just couldn't handle it.
He resigned his commission after a year and came back to A&M to make his home and married Roger Miller.
Of course, the war followed very quickly, and he was called right back to active duty.
And despite resigning that commission, he went on to become a lieutenant general, and we have our field name for him.
But because of that, when I graduated, I was the number one military graduate.
They had only one permanent commission to offer anyone in the Marine Department.
Colonel Converse S. Lewis called me in and he said, Lieutenant Conway, you've been selected for this award.
It's the greatest thing that could happen to you.
You're the only one.
I said, General Lewis, I can't take it.
He was astounded.
He got up from his desk and said, you can't do that.
it's too important, it's too great.
I said, well sir, I want a cotton fellowship to Europe and I'm a cotton, I want to get into cotton vendors and this is what I want to do.
And I said, you've got another man that's well qualified and more so than I am and I know wants this job and his name is Harry Shea.
Well Harry Shea took the job and I did.
One of the main reasons I didn't was because of Harmon's experience and the fact he dropped out.
Had he stayed in, maybe I would have.
I don't know.
You might have been a general.
I might have been killed going into Vietnam as a major, you know, too.
More likely.
Other student groups.
The band, they performed at what kinds of events?
Well, the band, I guess,

Well, the band, we had many cool reviews and the band was always the guts, you might say, to make it and give it the zip and the marching music that we, the old Sousa music and others that we just enjoyed marching to.
It just added so much
to our parades, and I remember one very distinct parade that was in my mind.
I was, as I say, I was commander of the Calvary Regiment, and about that time the armed services were recognizing that the Calvary was no longer a viable military force.
because the horse was so vulnerable.
So they were shutting down one of the, in Texas, one of the really historical great events, the Texas National Guard Calvary Regiment.
they decided to bring the flag of the National Guard Regiment to the A&M and present it to our cavalry regiment.
And there is Converse S. Lewis with Colonel Thompson, the commander at that time of the Calvary National Guard,
and his aid, and there I am accepting the flag at that memorial occasion.
It was a very significant occasion, but no one ever gives it a thought today, you know.
That flag is among some of our souvenirs, our memos there, souvenirs at A&M.
Well, let's hope it's still there.
It should be there.
Let's see, other student organizations,
Well, back to the band.
What did you non-band members think about the band?
Did you all hold it in high regard?
Did you respect and admire the band?
Oh, absolutely.
All of us did.
Of course, I never was a musical, never did play any instruments until my mother played the piano.
But I admired anyone who would volunteer their time to
All the trick, that sort of thing.
Plus I didn't have time for it because I was working for it.
Was there singing cadets in those days?
Yes, we had singing cadets.
But it was not anything like it is today.
Let's see, band director, who was the band director?
Can't remember.
Okay.
Yell leaders, what did the yell leaders do in those days?
They did the same thing they do today.
Old Cecil White was our year leader and Herbie Hartung, each class had two as I recall.
Both of them were dear friends of mine.
Both of them are no longer with us.
Herbie was a little redhead who was a jewel of a man and Cecil had a great personality and they were two leaders.
did a great job.
I have heard myths and reports about secret fraternities.
Can you share anything you heard about whether or not there were ever any secret fraternities?
I was never aware when I was a student that there was even secret fraternities around except
I think my junior, senior year, and I'm sure I was aware of it because I had one friend, Eddie Longoria, I remember I heard, but it didn't mean anything to me.
Because I was familiar with fraternities.
At the University of Georgia where my father went, I had some of my closest friends before I moved to Texas.
I always thought I would go to the University of Georgia sometime.
And when I was in high school there, a very unusual thing happened.
I was asked with a few of the other prominent young men to pledge K.A.
Severosa in high school as a senior.
They're trying to line up ahead of time, you know.
But that was the closest thing I ever came to any fraternity.
The only fraternity I ever detected was A&M fraternity, and it's the greatest in the world.
Summer jobs.
What did you do in the summers while you were an A&M undergraduate?
Well, I worked all summer in many varied jobs.
I worked for cotton farmers, Rand Morgan.
I kept books for him where he worked some 40, 50 Mexicans and had a little store there where they came in and they lived in little shacks.
But they'd come in and get their groceries and I'd have to check out and check them out to them and keep a record of what they did.
Worked there, keep a check of their hours.
That was one job I had.
I worked for a cotton generator and a cotton seed oil mill
one summer and I got a job with a freight broker because I was trying to work for different firms that dealt with cotton.
And I worked for Wheel Brothers Cotton Company one summer.
I was a reporter for the Call of Times and a proofreader for our paper here for several summers in high school
college.
But the main job I got was with the Ranges Converse Company as a shipping auto clerk, where I was responsible for shipping cotton all over the world, various cotton companies.
You were there four years.
About how much of your expenses for going to A&M did you earn yourself?
I would say 90%.
And what, in round numbers, what did a year cost?
Do you remember?
Well, back in old days, you know, a student could get by with as little as $2,500, probably.
So $3,000 overall.
And I'm sure even less.
times my buddy Omar must have gotten by and would almost have that.
Let's put on tape your, tell them your story about helping, you and others helping Omar Smith.
Omar Smith was in my troop, very troop, and he was an engaging guy.
He was a short
We called ourselves the Dusty Butch because we were the smallest one in the troop and right at the end of the lines, we lined up all in size.
And Omar and I became close friends.
Well, Omar was working his way through school like I was, except he was working at odd jobs.
And at times, when the quarterly payment came up for subsistence, he just couldn't, didn't have the money.
So he would go in and I'd invite him to come in and we'd put a mattress on the floor, an extra mattress we found.
He would sleep in my dormitory and I would bring him out food under my shirt.
I'd bring him out rolls, I'd bring him out a sandwich I'd make up, wrap it in a little napkin and a piece of pie, a kush, and others would do the same thing, bring a little fruit juice.
It had a plastic cap on it, and so he would go along for two or three weeks or a month at a time, by the way, until he could save enough money to go down and pay his assistant.
And he did that at least three or four times during his freshman, sophomore year.
And if we hadn't really do that, he would never have graduated.
But what happened to Omar?
Omar went on to become a very successful businessman in the Browns.
College Station area.

I think he ended up owning 40 or 50 Dairy Queen stores throughout Central and North Texas and volunteered to be the tennis coach and coached for about 10 years very successfully and thank God the school had the forethought to and the compassion to name the tennis court for Omar Smith.
I've participated in a memorial to him to the former Student Association at the time, and got several of my classmates to do the same.
And we all loved Omaha.
When you were going home to Corpus Christi, or going from Corpus Christi to College Station, how did you normally travel?
Hitchhiked.
describe hitchhiking from Corpus to, Corpus Christi to College Station?
Back in those days, it was not like today.
People were not afraid because there were, no one was ever, hardly ever attacked.
I had uniform and traveled in uniform wherever I could because people would pick up Texas Hikers, they would recognize them and they wanted to be helpful and
I could make almost as good time hitchhiking as I could if I rode the train.
In fact, I hitchhiked from, I wanted to go visit my grandparents in Georgia, Athens, Georgia, one Christmas.
I hitchhiked over there and I made better time than if I'd made on a train.
And I had no real problem with each time I'd make friends with a new family or some group.
share whatever they had with me, and it was a great adventure.
Now, if you were leaving the campus hitchhiking, where did you go to put out your thumb?
Was there a certain place?
Well, there were certain places, depending on the way you were going.
You were going to Houston, you were going to Austin, which you'd line up.
Where were those places?
You'd respect those in front of you and wait your turn.
A lot of times we'd get out there and a man said, well, I can carry four or five.
Throw that bucket four or five.
We'd all pile in and go as far as he'd take us.
Then we'd get out and do the same thing.
If you were hitchhiking, did you put out the thumb?
I just raised my hand, you know, and they recognized what we wanted.
We were in uniform, and it was a common practice.
How many of your outfit buddies had a car?
How common was it for a student to have a car then?
In my outfit, I think there was only one car, and the whole cavalry, there might have been three.
Were there...
In my opinion.
Did anybody ever borrow...
a buddy's car very much?
I didn't have any buddy that had one except I never did borrow any cars except I told you the case where I borrowed cases and if I was going to borrow a car I'd borrow his.
Let's see, a while ago I see a note here, we forgot to talk about P.L.
Downs.
Tell me about Pinky.
Oh, Pinky.
Well, Pinky, as I may have mentioned, ever since I graduated from A&M, my ties to A&M have always been so great because they did so much for me that I quickly got active in association affairs.
I made the annual association meetings and
got acquainted with all the old timers.
And I... What was the question?
Pinky.
Down.
Pinky.
Pinky was always there.
And Pinky was almost like a native of Bryan because he was born in, if I'm not mistaken, right near Waco over in
down there where he was a banker, if I recall correctly.
But he loved A&M so much that he kept coming back up there all the time.
And finally, he just moved his family up there and became an unofficial greeter.
And he'd walk around the campus, and anyone coming in, he'd introduce himself and see what he could do to help them, show them around.
Now, was he doing that when you were an undergraduate?
Oh, yeah.
Describe him physically.
Well, I say he was doing it without an undergraduate.
Yes, he was on that campus nearly all the time and I think he was a small thin man with his glasses and but a very friendly manner, very garrulous and he liked to talk about A&M.
He liked to show people around.
He was so proud of it.
Was Lupo there when you were an undergraduate?
Oh yeah, Lupo was
very much with his outfit.
I never did go and utilize his store, because I didn't need to, as many students did.
But Leupold was an institution, and still that he died.
Let's see.
Describe what it was like to try to get a date on an all-male campus.
How did an Aggie get a date?
Well, the dates that
Well, the girls I was interested in were either at the University or in Corpus Christi.
I didn't try to get any dates.
I corresponded with my dates at home or in Austin, or I'd go to see them when I could possibly get away, and I'd have them come see me for one of these ball weekends.
But there were a few lovely girls there in the Bryan area,
A few of them I remember.
It's kind of difficult right now.
About how often would you have a date come to College Station?
I had not.
No, no.
When one of the girls from Austin or... Oh, three or four times a semester, two or three times a semester.
Was it your task to pay her expenses?
No, no.
She paid all.
And they came, how did they get to College Station?
They'd come by train or out of the range for their parents or someone to bring them up.
Usually that way.
You told me that they stayed at the Aggieland Inn or in someone's home.
Where did they eat?
Aggieland Inn had a little restaurant there.
But you didn't take them into Sabeasa?
Oh yes, sometimes.
Sometimes.
There was special privileges on weekends that way you could take your date.
Did the routine at the dining table change when there were... Oh yes, oh yes.
It was all fun though.
Describe the community of College Station.
What was at the North Gate area?
Well, the Northgate area had a post office there that we utilized, and of course, Lou Pott was there, and he had a hamburger joint or two up there, and a bank there, and that's about it.
There wasn't any big operations, but we had a very small student body and a small campus there.
What was at Southgate?
Was there anything on Southside?
I think except the old primarily.
Over on the east side on the new highway?
On the new highway, of course, just beginning to blossom a little bit with saving a loan.
Had a small store or two.
You know, it wasn't, that would have been a day to go in there and buy four or five hundred acres.
How often did y'all go to Bryan?
Oh, once a month maybe.
How did you get there?
With each other.
And what was there in downtown Bryan that interested a young student?
The theater there and that was about it.
Just the novelty of getting off the A&M campus and going there for a special hamburger or something.
What major national or international events do you remember while you were a student?
Anything that you remember on the radio or in the newspaper that caught your attention?
Well, Roosevelt was president then.
things were happening in Europe, the Germans and the Nazi effort beginning to form some clouds, you know, around.
When I went to Europe, on the Cotton Fellowship, that was after I graduated.
at the summer of 1937.
We went through Germany and it was the only country where I went that I felt uncomfortable.

As you got on the trains and moved from one place to another, you see these brown shirted young men officially going through there and throwing their weight around and looking at you with question marks.
and maybe even asking you for identification and so forth.
And you'd see train load after train load as you passed on the tracks of caissons and artillery pieces and things moving.
And there was a feeling of uneasiness.
The only place I was robbed was in Cologne in a hotel.
My room was broken in there.
And when I went out for breakfast,
My purse was stolen.
Fortunately, I didn't have much money in it.
But I did have a few checks, but quickly had them exchanged.
But I still enjoyed Germany.
We took a trip down to Cologne, right by the front of Cologne, and down the river, the Rhine River.
It was an interesting trip.
But I felt uneasy there.
We all did.
Did you and other students listen to the president's fireside chats on the radio?
Did you all listen to Franklin Roosevelt?
Frankly, I didn't even have a radio in my room.
I didn't have time to do anything but study.
and work and go to sleep and eat.
That would put it well.
And take part in my cavalry activities and my monkey trail training and my tumbling team and a little fencing and that sort of thing.
Camaraderie with my little bit around with my friends.
Describe your dorm room.
How big was it?
What was in it?
Who was in it?
The dorm room I had was about half the size of this room, which is about, I'd say, about 15 by 30 or 25.
And we each had a Spartan desk chair.
We each had a double bunk in there.
I had a bunk each.
One place we had a double bunk.
and matches and springs, and we were responsible for keeping it clean, but it was spotty.
And what were the student indulgences of that time?
Did many students smoke, and if so, what did they smoke?
Well, they smoked cigarettes and they smoked cigars occasionally because there was a big man on the campus.
When you're a senior, you get some cigars every now and then.
What was the popular cigarette brand?
Lucky Strike, Chesterfield, Camel.
Were there any places off campus that students went to get alcoholic beverages?
Hard liquors, I never went there because I didn't have any money to spend for it, but also I wasn't a beer drinker.
I never went to hard liquors one time.
Hard liquors served beer?
They served beer.
Was there a place, it was, I know officially the county was dry, or I think it was.
Was there, were there places to buy whiskey?
The only thing I know about hot liggers is what I heard.
I never went in there to this day.
I never went in there.
Was there a bootlegger anywhere that you?
I heard that there was some available.
And I never knew where they were, but a friend like Bailey Conahan would know and Bailey would find who we needed for one of these special big dances and parties.
There was things to do to go out and have a little start.
It wasn't nobody else.
It wasn't offensive.
Was there alcohol at any of the social events?
Was there alcohol at the dances?
I'd say no, there was not any except you'd go outside and a few guys, you know, to show off more than yes, would have a pint of booze of some kind, moonshine.
Did any students use snuff or chewing tobacco?

You know, they would have been looking down at it pretty good if they did, and the rare, rare need that I recall, if ever seen, I'm sure we did have some shooting back then, but I was not conscious of it.
Did you even know the word marijuana?
No, never heard of it.
Didn't even know what it was until many years later in life.
Let's see, court trips.

Courtships we made once or twice a year, and of course as a Ross volunteer, we made one or two trips too, and as the courtships were special, we usually went into Fort Worth or Dallas, and we always arranged ahead of time for dates, or tried to, through our friends who lived in that area, and there were always occasions for
Special occasions for fun.
And y'all would, how did you get up to Fort Worth or Dallas, Houston or Austin?
Train, usually, or you'd make your own transportation arrangements.
And when did you leave?
Did you leave early Saturday morning or Friday afternoon?
I don't recall, but usually early Saturday morning, I'm sure, probably.
But by the time Friday afternoon, nothing could get old.
And then what happened, football games were, and day games, what happened on Saturday night?
Well, that's when we all got out and had our dates, and we saw the town, you know.
We wasn't doing anything but walking around with our dates around, with downtown lights and everything.
